flowRoot.flowPara: MFront is developped in the framework of the fuel simulation platform PLEIADES as a central part of its material knowledge management strategy and assurance quality policy.

MFront is an open-source code generator which translates a set of closely related domain specific languages (DSL) into plain C++ on top of the TFEL library. Those languages cover three kinds of material knowledge:
- material properties (for instance the Young modulus, the thermal conductivity, etc.).

- mechanical behaviours. Numerical performances of generated mechanical behaviours were given a particular attention. Various benchmarks show that MFront implementations are competitive with native implementations available in the Cast3M, Code-Aster and Cyrano3 solvers.
- simple point-wise models, such as material swelling used in fuel performance codes.

MFront can handle: small strain behaviours, finite strain behaviours and cohesive zone models. A wide variety of mechancial phenoma has already been treated: plasticity, viscoplasticity, damage, etc. A wide variety of materials have been modeleld : nuclear fuels, metals, concrete, etc.
MFront comes with a handy easy-to-use tool called MTest that can test the local behaviour of a material, by imposing independent constraints on each component of the strain or the stress.
MTest can handle small and finite strain behaviours and cohesive zone models.
MTest initial goal was to simplify the unit testing of MFront mechanical behaviours.

Thanks to a Python interface, MTest can be embedded in general purpose scientific environment to fit behaviour parameters against experimental data. In particular, MTest can be used in ADAO, a module for Data Assimilation and Optimization of the Salome platform.

MFront is based on the TFEL library which provides an optimised set of tensorial objects and operator overloading (tensors and symmetric tensors, 4 types of fourth order tensors).

To let the compiler perform an optimised code , MFront heavily relies on generic programming and template meta-programming: mechanical behaviours are implemented using template classes parametrized by the modelling hypothesis and the numeric type used (most solvers use double precision). A third template parameter will allow compile-time unit checks in the future. As a result, no heap allocated memory (except for behaviours working on large array of internal state variables) is used and all variables are stack allocated .

Mathematical operations rely on expression templates to eliminate temporaries. As the size of tensors is known at compile-time, the loop are also unrolled in most standard operations. More complex functions are specialized using the modelling hypothesis : no runtime-checks.
